{
  "title": "Criticisms of Pareto efficiency",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "b9a72ec2-850b-4f38-ba42-c83f69c7fff5",
      "text": "It would be incorrect to treat Pareto efficiency as equivalent to societal optimization, as the latter is a [[normative]] concept that is a matter of interpretation that typically would account for the consequence of degrees of inequality of distribution. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "03dae5b6d48bcba3",
      "text": "An example would be a school district with low property tax revenue versus one with much higher revenue. Generally, more equal distribution occurs with the help of government redistribution."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "afb92d8c-d04f-47b9-ac79-6382eee97c16",
      "text": "Pareto efficiency does not require a totally equitable distribution of wealth. An economy in which a wealthy few hold the vast majority of resources ([[Wealth condensation]]) can be Pareto efficient. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "493f57ae7a9c111d",
      "text": "This possibility is inherent in the definition of Pareto efficiency; often the [[status quo]] is Pareto efficient regardless of the degree to which wealth is equitably distributed. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "f5e16a632c670363",
      "text": "A simple example is the distribution of a pie among three people. The most equitable distribution would assign one third to each person. However the assignment of, say, a half section to each of two individuals and none to the third is also Pareto optimal despite not being equitable, because none of the recipients could be made better off without decreasing someone else's share; and there are many other such distribution examples. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "3092166b82ceb148",
      "text": "An example of a Pareto inefficient distribution of the pie would be allocation of a quarter of the pie to each of the three, with the remainder discarded. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "32407d555cbbebb2",
      "text": "The origin (and utility value) of the pie is conceived as immaterial in these examples. In such cases, whereby a \"windfall\" is gained that none of the potential distributees actually produced (e.g., land, inherited wealth, a portion of the broadcast spectrum, or some other resource), the criterion of Pareto efficiency does not determine a unique optimal allocation. Wealth consolidation may exclude others from wealth accumulation because of bars to market entry, etc."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "b826b626-ce67-4523-8443-0fdcec43d45b",
      "text": "The [[liberal paradox]] elaborated by [[Amartya Sen]] shows that when people have preferences about what other people do, the goal of Pareto efficiency can come into conflict with the goal of individual liberty."
    }
  ],
